<subSubSection id="C30F32F2DF1FFFE11EBE8D142A58FA13" pageId="24" pageNumber="1429" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BAA6179DF1FFFE11EBE8D142F4EFABA" blockId="24.[211,309,1323,1347]" box="[211,309,1323,1347]" pageId="24" pageNumber="1429">
<emphasis id="B961BD6BDF1FFFE11EBE8D142F4EFABA" box="[211,309,1323,1347]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="1429">Remarks</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BAA6179DF1FFFE11EBE8D6C2A58FA13" blockId="24.[211,1171,1363,1514]" pageId="24" pageNumber="1429">This species can be distinguished by these characters: pronotum has a sub-trapezoidal black spot in the disc and each elytron has four oblong spots and an indistinct spot at posterior one-third of elytral margin. Moreover, the elytra are moderately punctured; and the aedeagal apex is triangular. According to the original description, the spermathecal duct is loosely coiled dozens of times, and with a thicker base.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
